Using similar reasoning as the previous problem,

\begin{align*}
y(t) &= \pm \sqrt{k^2 \pm  |(k/2)^2-k^2| e^{-\lambda  t^2}} \\
&= \pm \sqrt{k^2 \pm |-3/4| k^2 e^{-\lambda  t^2}} \\
&= \pm k \sqrt{1 \pm 3/4 e^{-\lambda  t^2}} 
\end{align*}

When \emph{t}=0, \emph{y}(0)\textgreater{}0, so we need to take the
positive branch outside the square root:

\begin{align*}
y(t) = + |k| \sqrt{1 \pm 3/4 e^{-\lambda  t^2}} = k\sqrt{1 \pm 3/4 e^{-\lambda  t^2}},
\end{align*}

again the last equality holding since \emph{k} is positive. If we
evaluate this at \emph{t}=0, the positive branch gives
$y(0) = k \sqrt{1 + 3/4}  = \sqrt{7}k/2$, which is wrong, since
\emph{y}(0)=\emph{y}\textsubscript{0}=\emph{k}/2. Hence this is the
wrong branch. Indeed, the negative branch gives
$y(0) = k \sqrt{1 - 3/4} = k/2.$ Our answer is therefore

\begin{align*}
y(t) = k \sqrt{1 - 3/4 e^{-\lambda  t^2}},
\end{align*}

As $t \to \infty$ we have that $y(t) \to k.$

